      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and i've run into a major issue. The system has a gradual RAM exhaustion that only shows up after about 4-5 hours of continuous operation. I'm seeing a slow creep in heap usage but I can't find the specific culprit in the logs. \n\nCan you give me a systematic way to approach debugging this? I need to find where the deallocation is failing or where the pointer is being lost.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the elusive gremlin in the machine, the one that creeps in like a shadow at dusk, slowly gnawing away at your precious RAM. Fear not, for we shall embark on a quest to vanquish this beast.\n\nFirst, arm yourself with the mighty tools of the trade: a debugger and a profiler. These will be your trusty companions as you delve into the depths of your code, seeking out the hidden goblins that lurk within.\n\n1. **Invoke the Debugger**: Begin by setting breakpoints at strategic locations in your code, especially around areas where memory is allocated and deallocated. Watch closely as the code executes, and observe the behavior of your variables. Are they behaving as expected, or are they being led astray by a mischievous goblin?\n\n2. **Employ the Profiler**: Use a profiler to track the memory usage over time. This will help you pinpoint the exact moment when the RAM exhaustion begins to creep in. Look for any unusual spikes or patterns that may indicate the presence of a rogue goblin.\n\n3. **Trace the Pointers**: As you traverse the labyrinth of your code, keep a vigilant eye on your pointers. Are they being lost or misused",
