      "role": "user",
      "content": "The \"gremlin/goblin\" metaphors aren't helping me actually solve the leak—I need technical specifics. Since I'm on an embedded system with limited resources, I can't just run a heavy profiler. \n\nCan you suggest some lightweight, low-level techniques for an ECU environment? I'm looking for things like custom allocator wrappers or heap monitoring hooks that won't tank the real-time performance. How do I actually track which specific module is responsible for the creep?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's get down to the brass tacks of embedded systems and tackle this RAM exhaustion with precision and efficiency.\n\n1. **Custom Allocator Wrappers**: Implement a custom memory allocator for your embedded system. This allocator can wrap around the standard allocation functions and provide additional logging or tracking capabilities. By doing so, you can monitor each allocation and deallocation, and potentially catch any mismanagement of memory.\n\n2. **Heap Monitoring Hooks**: Integrate heap monitoring hooks into your system. These hooks can be lightweight and designed to trigger only when certain conditions are met, such as reaching a specific memory threshold. This way, you can minimize the performance impact while still keeping an eye on memory usage.\n\n3. **Module-Specific Logging**: Enhance your logging mechanism to include module-specific information. Whenever a memory allocation or deallocation occurs, log the module name along with the operation. This will help you trace back the source of the leak to a specific module.\n\n4. **Static Analysis Tools**: Utilize static analysis tools to scan your code for potential memory leaks and pointer mismanagement. These tools can help you identify problematic areas in your code without the need for extensive runtime monitoring.\n\n5. **Code Review and Pair Programming",
      "source": "target",
