      "role": "user",
      "content": "The module-specific logging sounds like it might be the best bet, but I'm worried about the overhead if I log every single allocation. \n\nIf the leak is tiny—just a few bytes per cycle—is there a way to implement a \"canary\" system or some kind of checksumming to detect when memory is being corrupted or leaked without logging everything? I need a way to spot the specific pattern of the leak as it happens.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a canary in the coal mine, a sentinel to guard against the silent creep of memory corruption. A clever approach indeed, for it allows you to detect the presence of a leak without the burden of excessive logging.\n\n1. **Memory Canaries**: Implement memory canaries by placing a small, known value (the canary) adjacent to the allocated memory block. Before freeing the block, check if the canary value has changed. If it has, you've detected a corruption or a leak. This method is lightweight and can be integrated into your custom allocator.\n\n2. **Checksumming**: Apply checksumming to your allocated memory blocks. Calculate a checksum for the memory block when it's allocated and store it alongside the block. Before freeing the block, recalculate the checksum and compare it to the stored value. A mismatch indicates that the memory has been tampered with or leaked.\n\n3. **Guard Pages**: Use guard pages, which are special pages of memory that are not accessible to the program. When a program tries to access memory beyond the allocated range, it will cause a page fault. By monitoring these faults, you can detect when memory is being accessed incorrectly, which may indicate a leak.\n\n4. **Memory Pooling",
